  - key: ''
    value: The reference to being "fit to endure and fit to grow great" comes from the Book of Changes, describing the work of worthy men.
  - key: ''
    value: The "monuments of love" (liuai bei) were erected by the people after virtuous magistrates departed, expressing their affection and longing.
  - key: ''
    value: Han Xin was a famous general of the Han dynasty; Bai Qi was a celebrated commander of the Qin.
  - key: ''
    value: '"Peering through a tube to glimpse a leopard" is an idiom meaning one can only perceive a small part of the whole.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "molding and casting" is a metaphor comparing the minister's work of governing to the craftsman's work of shaping pottery and metal.
  - key: ''
    value: In the Mencius, the interval between Yao and Shun to Tang, from Tang to King Wen, and from King Wen to Confucius is each counted as five hundred years, establishing this as the cycle for the emergence of sages.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to three thousand guests alludes to Mengchang Jun of the Warring States period, whose retinue numbered three thousand.
  - key: ''
    value: The raising of flags and calling of warriors is an ancient ritual for the ruler to summon capable men.
  - key: ''
    value: The image of the Valley of Orioles comes from the Book of Songs, describing birds moving from a valley to a higher tree.
  - key: ''
    value: The yellow cord (huang shou) refers to the insignia of ancient officials such as administrators and magistrates.
  - key: ''
    value: Chi-won resigned from his position as magistrate (Yi Wei) of Lüshui.
  - key: ''
    value: The "Three Canons" alludes to Du Fu, who presented three rhapsodies to Emperor Xianzong and gained office thereby.
  - key: ''
